<subsection xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"><title> Special Cases </title>
    
    <p>
        A differential equation can still be <xref ref="def-separable" text="custom">separable</xref> even if one or both of the variables, <m>x</m> or <m>y</m>, do not appear in the equation. For example, the differential equation,
        <me> \frac{dy}{dx} = x^2 </me>
        is technically separable since it can be written as 
        <me> \frac{dy}{dx} = (\underset{f(x)}{\underset{\uparrow}{ \vphantom{|} x^2 }}) \cdot (\underset{g(y)}{\underset{\uparrow}{ \vphantom{|} 1 }}) </me>
        where <m>g(y)</m> is a constant function. The same concept applies if the <m>x</m> variable is missing.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="special-separable-forms-examples"><title> Special Separable Differential Equations </title>

        <p>
            The following first-order differential equations are separable.
            <tabular>
                <row><cell><m/></cell></row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = 6x + 5 </m></cell>
                    <cell/>
                    <cell><m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = (y - 6)^3</m></cell>
                    <cell/>
                    <cell><m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = 15</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </p>

    </example>

    <xi:include href="../interactives/sov-special-cases-interactives.ptx" />

</subsection>
